benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/admin/queues - Get queues entries

covered: Valid Request: Multiple scenarios (TC01-TC10, TC22, TC23) validate successful retrieval with valid parameters and combinations (including default flag behaviour).
Response type and success code: TC01 asserts 200 and application/octet-stream for the default case (matches acceptance criteria).

Query Parameters: accountId (TC02, TC13, TC14), queueName (TC03), serviceName (TC04), minDate/maxDate (TC05, TC24, TC25), and flags withHistory/withInProcessing/withBusEvents/withNotifications (TC06-TC09, TC21) are explicitly tested, including combined usage (TC10).
Empty Responses: TC11 and TC29 cover no-data and filters-exclude-all-data cases.
Error handling: 400 invalid inputs (TC13, TC25), 404 account not found (TC14), 500 internal server error (TC30), 503 service unavailable (TC16), and 504 timeout (TC19) are present.
Security: Injection and XSS attempts are addressed (TC17, TC26) and ensure no internal errors or script execution.
Performance & resilience: Large dataset performance (TC18), timeout (TC19), concurrent requests (TC20), and transient network recovery (TC27) are included.
Robustness/UX: Extra/unexpected parameters (TC12), regression (TC21), backward compatibility (TC22), and API docs/error schema accessibility (TC28) are included.
gaps: Pagination: No tests cover pagination (page/limit/offset) or streaming/page-wise consumption for large datasets; critical for GET endpoints and large-volume retrievals.
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No scenarios verify rate limiting behaviour, HTTP 429 handling, or throttling under burst traffic.
Caching Behavior: No tests validate caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional GET semantics.
403 / Role-based authorization: Only 401 unauthorized is tested. There is no test for forbidden access (403) or role/permission enforcement for non-admin callers.

Content-type and streaming validation across scenarios: application/octet-stream is asserted only in TC01; other scenarios (filtered responses, large-volume, error responses) don't consistently assert content-type, streaming integrity, or how the octet-stream is encoded/framed.

Pagination-related performance and memory: While large-volume retrieval (TC18) exists, there's no test that combines large volume with pagination to ensure memory/streaming behavior (e.g., server-side limits).
Rate-limiting vs concurrency: TC20 covers concurrency correctness but not interaction of concurrency with rate-limiting or degraded responses (429).

Negative combination/parameter boundary cases: Some boundary cases for booleans, extreme date bounds, or malformed but syntactically valid UUIDs are not exhaustively covered beyond the basic malformed/invalid cases.
recommendations: Add pagination tests: verify page, limit, offset parameters (or whatever pagination the API uses), verify correct slicing, total-count semantics (if applicable), and behavior when requesting pages outside range.
Add rate-limiting tests: simulate burst requests to assert 429 responses and retry-after behavior; verify graceful degradation.
Add caching tests: assert presence and correctness of Cache-Control, ETag/If-None-Match, Last-Modified/If-Modified-Since headers and behavior for conditional requests (304).
Add role/permission tests: include 403 forbidden scenarios for authenticated users lacking admin privileges, and tests for different auth schemes if supported.

Assert content-type and streaming across scenarios: check application/octet-stream (and any Content-Encoding) for filtered, empty, large-volume and error responses; validate that the octet-stream can be consumed/parsed as expected.
Combine pagination with large-volume tests to ensure acceptable memory/latency characteristics and to validate server-side streaming or chunking behaviour.
Expand negative/boundary testing: additional malformed but valid-structure UUIDs, boolean param edge cases, overlapping/contradictory date ranges (minDate > maxDate) and large/small date bounds.
Add rate-limiting + concurrency combined tests and long-running/slow-client scenarios to validate stability under load.
